==Athletics==<!-- This section is linked from [[Phoenix]] -->
{{see|Elon Phoenix basketball|Elon Phoenix soccer|Elon Phoenix baseball|}}
[[File:ElonPhoenix.png|right|thumb|150px|Phoenix logo]]
Elon's 16 varsity sports teams, known as the Phoenix, compete in the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]]'s Division I [[Southern Conference]].  Intercollegiate sports include [[baseball]], [[basketball]], [[cross country running|cross-country]], [[American football|football]], [[golf]], [[soccer]], and [[tennis]] for men, and [[basketball]], [[cross country running|cross-country]], [[golf]], indoor [[Track and field|track]], outdoor [[Track and field|track]], [[soccer]], [[softball]], [[tennis]], and [[volleyball]] for women. The football team competes in the [[Division I FCS|Division I Football Championship Subdivision]] (formerly I-AA).

Campus Recreation offers intramural and club sports programs, such as baseball, cycling, [[lacrosse]], [[flag football]], [[equestrianism|equestrian]], swimming, [[rugby union]], [[triathlon]], [[water skiing]], ice hockey and [[Ultimate (sport)|Ultimate Frisbee]]. During Winter Term the intramurals include bowling, arena football, dodgeball, ultimate frisbee, and a monster golf tournament.

[[Image:Fightiinchristian.jpg|right|thumb|130px|The Elon Fightin' Christian Emblem]]
Up until 2000, the mascot of Elon was the Fighting Christian.  The moniker is said to have been coined by a sportswriter covering a contest in the 1930s between Elon and nearby [[Guilford College]], a Quaker school. (Prior to the 1930s, Elon had been known by several different nicknames.)  The nickname was chosen due to Elon's proximity to the [[Wake Forest University|Wake Forest]] Demon Deacons, and the [[Duke University|Duke]] Blue Devils.{{citation needed|date=October 2011}}  However, many did not feel that the nickname was universal enough for a team making the transition to Division I athletics,{{citation needed|date=October 2011}} so a new mascot was adopted in 2000, the [[Phoenix (mythology)|Phoenix]].  The choice came from the 1923 fire that destroyed almost the entire campus.  Soon after the fire, the university trustees began planning to make Elon "rise from the ashes".  The Phoenix was a mythical creature that rose from the ashes of its predecessors.

Elon's Fight Song was written in 1921 by Mark Z. Rhodes to the tune of F.E. Bigelow's march "Our Director."

<blockquote>
So here's to dear old Elon<br>
Faithful and bold<br>
Here's to her banner<br>
Of maroon and gold<br>
Here's to men and women<br>
Who've come and gone<br>
Singing the victor's song<br>
Of old Elon<br>
</blockquote>

=== Facilities ===
Elon's sports facilities include two gymnasiums, Walter C. Latham Baseball Park, [[Rhodes Stadium]], the on-campus [[American football|football]] stadium, Alumni Field House, Koury Field House, six club athletic fields, Worseley Golf Center, and Koury Center, which features the 2,400 seat [[Alumni Gym (Elon University)|Alumni Gym]], an aerobic fitness center, a weight room, [[racquetball]] courts, an indoor pool, and a dance studio. The Jimmy Powell Tennis Center is a twelve-court state-of-the-art complex and is recognized as one of the finest collegiate tennis complexes in the nation.<ref>[http://www.usta.com/USTA/Global/Get_Involved/Awards/Information/155336_USTA_Outstanding_Facility_Awards.aspx USTA Outstanding Facility Awards | USTA<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Athletics staff and coaches began the move into Alumni Field House on Jan. 14. The {{convert|30000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} facility at the north end of Rhodes Stadium in the North Athletics Complex is the new headquarters for Phoenix athletics.<ref>[http://www.elon.edu/e-net/Note.aspx?id=949946&board_ids=5&max=5 E-Net! News & Information<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>

== Campus ==
{{Main|Elon University campus}}

Elon's historic campus is located in the [[Piedmont (United States)|Piedmont]] region of [[North Carolina]], adjacent to [[Burlington, North Carolina|Burlington]], a city of 50,000. Elon is just 20 minutes from [[Greensboro, North Carolina|Greensboro]] and within a one hour drive of major universities — [[Duke University|Duke]], [[NC State]], [[UNC-Chapel Hill]], [[UNC-Greensboro]], [[North Carolina A&T State University]], and [[Wake Forest University|Wake Forest]].

[[Princeton Review]] has recognized Elon University for having one of the nation's most beautiful campuses. The wooded grounds have been designated a [[botanical garden]]. Elon's {{convert|600|acre|ha|1|sing=on}} campus is divided into seven major sections: North Area, Central Campus, West Area, East Area, South Campus, Danieley Center, and Elon West.  Each area consists of different services and facilities.  There are 29 residence buildings on campus and 12 major academic buildings.  Elon also has numerous lakes and fountains throughout its campus.

[[Spike Lee]] used Elon as one of the university locations for the movie ''[[He Got Game]]''. The Alamance Building, Fonville Fountain, and the Moseley Center's outside patio were the setting for the movie's "Tech University."

== Campus Life ==
The university has more than 150 campus organizations and programs, including 12 national [[fraternities]] and 13 national [[sororities]].

''[[The Pendulum (newspaper)|The Pendulum]]'', Elon's undergraduate weekly [[newspaper]] is published every Wednesday.  [[WSOE]], the University's student-run [[non-commercial]] [[campus radio]] station, has been airing since 1977.  ETV (Elon Television) is the [[Student television station]] featuring numerous student-created and -run programs in addition to its nationally recognized news program, [http://phoenix14news.wordpress.com/ Phoenix14 News], produced by ESTV (Elon Student Television). Phoenix14News was ranked #1 college newscast by the Broadcast Education Association in 2009 and was recognized as the Best College Newscast by the Academy of Television Arts and Sciences.

Numerous student government, [[special interest]], and [[Non-profit organization|service organizations]] are represented on campus, including Elon Volunteers, [[Habitat for Humanity]], [[Model UN]], [[Epsilon Sigma Alpha]], [[Alpha Phi Omega]], the Resident Student Association, the [[Elon University Student Government Association|Student Government Association]], and the Student Union Board. Cultural groups on campus include the Black Cultural Society, [[Hillel: The Foundation for Jewish Campus Life|Hillel]], Intercultural Club, and Spectrum (Gay-Straight Alliance).

Elon is home to the [http://org.elon.edu/music/ensembles/band/marchingband.html Fire of the Carolinas Marching Band (FOTC)], which delivers pre-game, halftime, and occasionally post-game performances at home [[American football|football]] games. The band also includes [[color guard (flag spinning)]] and [[dance]] auxiliary squads.

=== Religious life ===

Religious groups on campus include [[Catholic]] Campus Ministry, [[Hillel: The Foundation for Jewish Campus Life including Greg Ehrenberg]], [[InterVarsity Christian Fellowship]], [[Baptist Student Union]], [[Sigma Alpha Omega]], and [[Campus Outreach]].<ref name="autogenerated2">[http://www.elon.edu/e-web/students/religious_life/organizations.xhtml Elon University - Office of Religious Life<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>  

The [[Jewish]] population at Elon has grown especially rapidly in recent years, with eight percent of recent classes self-identifying as Jewish,<ref>[http://www.elon.edu/pendulum/Story.aspx?id=5006 The Pendulum - Various religious groups growing in number on campus<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[http://reformjudaismmag.org/Articles/index.cfm?id=1368 Reform Judaism Magazine - Admissions 101: Unexpected Suitors<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[http://www.elon.edu/e-web/students/hillel/climate.xhtml, accessed June 15, 2011: 8% of the students in the class of 2014 have identified themselves as Jewish; 8% of the early action and early decision applicants to the class of 2015 have identified themselves as Jewish.]</ref><ref>"Elon to welcome professor of Jewish studies in the fall," http://www.elon.edu/pendulum/Story.aspx?id=5275</ref><ref>Burlington Times News, "Students hope for Jewish fraternity on Elon campus," http://www.thetimesnews.com/articles/elon-44261-jewish-students.html</ref> though the number of Jewish students on campus is assumed by some to be higher than this.<ref>[http://www.elon.edu/pendulum/Story.aspx?id=5631 The Pendulum - Development of Jewish Studies program progressing<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>  Elon was recently profiled in ''Reform Judaism'' magazine as a school which has "gone the extra mile" to make itself more attractive to Jewish students.<ref>Admissions 105: Unexpected Welcomes, by Claire D. Friedlander, reformjudaismmag.org/Articles/index.cfm?id=2865</ref>

A [[Muslim]] Student Association is currently in development at Elon.<ref name="autogenerated2"/> 

There are only a handful of Hindu students at Elon, and no formal Hindu organization on campus, though Hindu students report feeling accepted at Elon.<ref>[http://www.elon.edu/pendulum/Story.aspx?id=4209 The Pendulum - Hindu students faithful at Elon, even without formal organization<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>

Elon has received praise for its efforts to build a multi-faith center that is open to students of all religious traditions.<ref>[http://www.topnews.in/hindus-laud-prestigious-elon-university-over-construction-plans-multifaith-center-2163149 Hindus laud prestigious Elon University over construction plans of multi-faith center]</ref>

=== Greek Life ===
Elon University recognizes 25 social Greek organizations.  43% of women and 26% of men on campus belong to one of the following campus-chartered organizations. In 2011, two new Greek organizations were installed, one IFC fraternity ([[Delta Upsilon]]) and one PHC sorority ([[Kappa Delta]]).
